<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n58060b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n58" href="#n58060b">N58 (VI.B.30)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n58all.htm#n58060b"> 60(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <u>plant</u> / sun = spring / S in / branches = E / struggle / &amp; / ricefield = M</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A true noun, an isolated thing, does not exist in nature. Things are only the terminal points, or rather the meeting points of actions, cross-sections cut through actions, snap-shots. Neither can a pure verb, an abstract motion, be possible in nature. The eye sees noun and verb as one: things in motion, motion in things, and so the Chinese conception tends to represent them. <p><mark>The sun underlying the bursting forth of plants = spring</mark>.</p> <p><mark>The sun sign tangled in the branches of the tree sign = east</mark>.</p> <p><mark>&ldquo;Rice-field&rdquo; plus &ldquo;struggle&rdquo; = male</mark>.</p> <p>&ldquo;Boat&rdquo; plus &ldquo;water,&rdquo; boat-water, a ripple.</p> <small> Ernest Fenollosa, &ldquo;The Chinese Written Character as a Medium for Poetry&rdquo;, in <a name="EFCW" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EFCW"><cite title="source">Instigations of Ezra Pound</cite></a> (1920) 364</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="sa0511x" href="saall.htm#sa0511x">SA (VI.A):0511(x)</a>. An orange mark appears under this unit.</mm> </dd></dl>
